		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">Making unauthorized copies of a video game that has never been published in a given country is still copyright infringement.<br /></div><br /><br />I suppose technically, yes it is; however it is very unlikely that any company is going to go after a small-fry such as myself, or even this board as a whole, for doing that. If anything, it actually helps the developers, because it could end up leading to future purchases. Whereas without these reproduction carts, english players would not have access to these games. <br /><br />Such as you and Dwedit have said, yes there are Super Famicom carts, but you'd have to know Japanese to understand them. As a double major that is already learning Chinese at the moment; I can't really do that. Likewise, most people cannot.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">Fear of lawsuit over facilitating copyright infringement, perhaps.</div>
<br />
<br />As I said before, the odds of NoA going after this message board over somebody teaching another person how to do this, is incredibly unlikely. They would sooner go after the big fish in the pond, and sue the people who are distributing the ROM files that other people are using to make these reproduction carts. 
<br />Suing people that make the carts, and the people that taught them how, would make little to no sense from a copyright and business standpoint. (Unless the person becomes a huge seller and is making a bunch of money selling these carts, and are also selling games that <strong>have </strong>already been released in America)

		

