	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b></b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />Bregalad was not really being rude. This new piracy under the vale of "Reproductions" is quite a troublesome issue. People tend to deny or write off that this is bootlegging and copyright violation. While I personally don't care so much about bootlegging of games from the 90s, when it is done for profit or solely because someone else provided a free translation it bothers me. 
<br />
<br />People that put all the effort and time into making a translation of a game like Seiken Densetsu 3 or Star Ocean certainly wouldn't appreciate somebody making a profit selling bootlegged versions of their translation to people. 
<br />
<br />Just in general, once someone is profiting from piracy it's bothersome. If you want to make your own for your personal collection I'm not as bothered by it. I can see the appeal in having these games to play on your console. However first I must recommend using a Flash Cartridge. Flash Cartridges allow you to play these games without messing with original cartridges.
<br />
<br />But if you're dead set on making your own bootleg cartridge, do us all a favor and don't be wasteful. Use donor games that are absolutely horrible and won't be missed. 
<br />
<br />Offering a "service" to build reproductions for people is problematic. While if you maintain the same price for your workmanship and parts (and accept them providing the parts themselves) you can argue they are paying you for your time. 
<br />
<br />The problem comes with people like the gamereproductions site which seems to have a bunch of different prices for different games. Given that the process for many of these games is the exact same, clearly you are not paying for something honest.
<br />
<br />One of those sites I believe sells Star Fox 2 for $100. I recall someone arguing with me somewhere saying that they were told (by whoever was selling them) that it was the cheapest it could be sold for or something like that. This is utter garbage. If you want to build a Star Fox 2 cartridge you only need an EPROM, soldering iron (+misc soldering accessories), wire, and some time. The parts to build such a cartridge could be obtained for as little as $10. That's $90 of potential profit. I'm certain you could do that in less than an hour. I'd love to make $90 per hour. But I don't believe such a thing is morally right, and it's also very illegal.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


