		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">MottZilla wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Bregalad was not really being rude. This new piracy under the vale of "Reproductions" is quite a troublesome issue. People tend to deny or write off that this is bootlegging and copyright violation. While I personally don't care so much about bootlegging of games from the 90s, when it is done for profit or solely because someone else provided a free translation it bothers me. <br /><br />People that put all the effort and time into making a translation of a game like Seiken Densetsu 3 or Star Ocean certainly wouldn't appreciate somebody making a profit selling bootlegged versions of their translation to people. <br /><br />Just in general, once someone is profiting from piracy it's bothersome. If you want to make your own for your personal collection I'm not as bothered by it. I can see the appeal in having these games to play on your console. However first I must recommend using a Flash Cartridge. Flash Cartridges allow you to play these games without messing with original cartridges.<br /><br />But if you're dead set on making your own bootleg cartridge, do us all a favor and don't be wasteful. Use donor games that are absolutely horrible and won't be missed. <br /><br />Offering a "service" to build reproductions for people is problematic. While if you maintain the same price for your workmanship and parts (and accept them providing the parts themselves) you can argue they are paying you for your time. <br /><br />The problem comes with people like the gamereproductions site which seems to have a bunch of different prices for different games. Given that the process for many of these games is the exact same, clearly you are not paying for something honest.<br /><br />One of those sites I believe sells Star Fox 2 for $100. I recall someone arguing with me somewhere saying that they were told (by whoever was selling them) that it was the cheapest it could be sold for or something like that. This is utter garbage. If you want to build a Star Fox 2 cartridge you only need an EPROM, soldering iron (+misc soldering accessories), wire, and some time. The parts to build such a cartridge could be obtained for as little as $10. That's $90 of potential profit. I'm certain you could do that in less than an hour. I'd love to make $90 per hour. But I don't believe such a thing is morally right, and it's also very illegal.</div>
<br />
<br />
<br />I do have to say, you make a pretty solid point.
<br />
<br />And honestly, I want to learn this more for my own enjoyment, rather than to make a profit. I wouldn't be making a website like gamereproductions.com; it would be a website based around video walkthroughs for older games, with these games that have never been released in America included. 
<br />On the side, I was considering also offering a service for making reproductions for these games, as I already said, but I agree with you when gamereproductions.com's prices are borderline robbery.
<br />
<br />IF, and that's a big IF, I decide to offer a service where I will make people a reproduction cart of their choice in conjunction with the website I want to build, I would only charge a very small fee for my time, in addition for the fees it costs for parts. Rest assured, I would never charge more than like...$5-$10 extra than what the parts cost. That's it. It wouldn't be some big storefront like gamereproductions.com is.
<br />
<br />I'm not looking to make a profit off of this knowledge, I merely want to be able to provide these games to other people who never got the chance to play the game in English, on their consoles. That's what I've always wanted to do: Play these games on the console. And I'm sure there are other people out there like that.
<br />
<br />In fact, this whole situation started when I was ripped off myself. I bought an NES cartridge for Earthbound, thinking it was a legitimate release of the game that was just really hard to find, for $100 on eBay. 
<br />Little did I know, that the game never actually got released in the US, and that I just purchased something for $75 more than what I could have paid at another website.
<br />
<br />This is the very reason I want to learn: To help stop people from getting ripped off. Like I said in my original post, I never even knew about reproduction carts until two days ago when I got ripped off. 
<br />If I can create a successful community based around these non-american-released games, and if I could make these games for those community members to play; WITHOUT them having to pay $60-$100 like on gamereproductions.com, then I would be extremely happy.
<br />
<br />If you notice, the SNES cartridges are a lot more expensive on that website than the NES carts. That is because nobody else online offers the same service. There are a handful of other competitive websites that sell NES reproductions, but there are NO other websites that sell SNES reproductions. Which is exactly why he can sell them for $60-$100 a pop. And it's also exactly where my idea stems from. 
<br />But I can't stop people from getting ripped off, and simultaneously let people have those games on their consoles, without first learning how to make these reproductions myself. 
<br />
<br />With that said: If anybody is willing to take me under their wing, I would love to learn.

		

		</td>
